{
  "local_port": 43406,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does HDMI over Fiber work?",
  "response": "HDMI over Fiber, also known as HDMI Fiber Optic Extender, is a technology that transmits high-definition multimedia interface (HDMI) signals over fiber optic cables. This method is used to extend the reach of HDMI signals beyond the limitations of traditional HDMI copper cables, which typically have a maximum length of around 15 meters (50 feet) before signal degradation becomes an issue.\n\nHere's how HDMI over Fiber works:\n\n1. **Signal Conversion:**\n   - At the transmitting end, an HDMI over Fiber transmitter converts the electrical HDMI signal into an optical signal. This conversion is necessary because fiber optic cables transmit data using light rather than electricity.\n\n2. **Transmission:**\n   - The optical signal is then sent through a fiber optic cable. Fiber optic cables can transmit data over much longer distances with minimal signal loss compared to copper cables. Depending on the quality of the fiber optic cable and the specific technology used, HDMI over Fiber can transmit signals over distances ranging from 30 meters to several kilometers.\n\n3. **Signal Reception:**\n   - At the receiving end, an HDMI over Fiber receiver converts the optical signal back into an electrical HDMI signal. This signal can then be connected to a display device such as a TV or monitor.\n\n4. **Additional Features:**\n   - Many HDMI over Fiber systems also support the transmission of other signals, such as IR (infrared) for remote control functionality, RS-232 for control signals, and even Ethernet for network connectivity. This makes them versatile solutions for various applications, including home theater setups, digital signage, and professional AV installations.\n\n5. **Advantages:**\n   - **Longer Distance:** The primary advantage of HDMI over Fiber is the ability to transmit high-quality HDMI signals over much longer distances than traditional HDMI cables.\n   - **Immunity to Electromagnetic Interference (EMI):** Fiber optic cables are not susceptible to electromagnetic interference, making them ideal for use in environments with high levels of electrical noise.\n   - **High Bandwidth:** Fiber optic cables can support high bandwidth, which is essential for transmitting high-resolution video and audio signals.\n\n6. **Applications:**\n   - HDMI over Fiber is commonly used in settings where long-distance, high-quality video transmission is required, such as in conference rooms, stadiums, educational institutions, and broadcasting facilities.\n\nIn summary, HDMI over Fiber technology extends the capabilities of HDMI by converting and transmitting its signals over fiber optic cables, allowing for longer distances and higher quality without the risk of signal degradation or interference.",
